solution:
因为按照题意，电磁波是平面单色波，即

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{E}=\boldsymbol{E}_{0} e^{-\mathrm{i} \omega t} \tag{5}
\end{equation*}

则方程（4）可以写成

\begin{equation*}
\ddot{\boldsymbol{r}}+\omega_{0}^{2} \boldsymbol{r}+2 \delta \dot{\boldsymbol{r}}=\frac{e}{m} \boldsymbol{E}_{0} e^{-\mathrm{i} \omega t} \tag{6}
\end{equation*}

其中 $\omega_{0}=\sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}$ 为电子在原子（分子）中振动的"固有"频率， $\delta=g / 2m$ 为衰减系数，而 $\boldsymbol{E}_{0}$ 为电磁波中电场强度的振幅。

我们假设方程（6）的解具有如下形式：

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{r}=\boldsymbol{r}_{0} e^{-\mathrm{i} \omega t} \tag{7}
\end{equation*}

其中 $\boldsymbol{r}_{0}$ 为电子位移的振幅。将式（7）代入式（6）并做必要的微商，则可得到

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{r}_{0}=\frac{(e / m) \boldsymbol{E}_{0}}{\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2} - 2\mathrm{i} \delta \omega\right)} \tag{8}
\end{equation*}

由此可见，在平面波外电场作用下，非极性分子获得偶极矩

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{p}=e \boldsymbol{r}=\frac{e^{2} \boldsymbol{E}}{m\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2} - 2\mathrm{i} \delta \omega\right)} \tag{9}
\end{equation*}

按照定义，介质的极化强度矢量的表达式为

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{P}=N \boldsymbol{p}=\frac{e^{2} N \boldsymbol{E}}{m\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2} - 2\mathrm{i} \delta \omega\right)} \tag{10}
\end{equation*}

其中 $N$ 为单位体积中的分子数目。由式（10）可以看出，介质的极化强度矢量与外电场强度成正比，当 $\delta \neq 0$ 时，比例系数为复数。

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{P}=\varepsilon_{0} \alpha \boldsymbol{E} \tag{11}
\end{equation*}

系数 $\alpha$ 在此情况下称作介质的极化率。将式（10）和式（11）加以比较，得出

\begin{equation*}
\alpha=\frac{e^{2} N}{\varepsilon_{0} m\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2} - 2\mathrm{i} \delta \omega\right)} \tag{12}
\end{equation*}

\[
\begin{aligned}
& F=\frac{\mathrm{d} p}{\mathrm{d} t}=\frac{1}{c} \frac{\mathrm{d} E}{\mathrm{d} t} \\
& t=\frac{v}{a}=\frac{v}{F/m}=\frac{m v c}{\mathrm{d} E / \mathrm{d} t}=\frac{100 \times 1 \times 3 \times 10^{8}}{10 \times 10^{3}}=3 \times 10^{6} \, \text{s}
\end{aligned}
\]

It would take approximately one month to reach a speed of \(1 \, \mathrm{m/s}\).

problem:
一原子四个最低能级态为

\[ E_{0}=-14.0 \, \mathrm{eV}, \quad E_{1}=-9.0 \, \mathrm{eV}, \quad E_{2}=-7.0 \, \mathrm{eV}, \quad E_{3}=-5.5 \, \mathrm{eV} \]

对 \(i \rightarrow j\) 跃迁的跃迁率 \(A_{ij}\) (Einstein 系数) 为

\[
\begin{aligned}
& A_{20} = 1.2 \times 10^{8} \, \mathrm{s}^{-1}, \quad A_{21} = 8.0 \times 10^{7} \, \mathrm{s}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

计算 \(E_{2}\) 能级的辐射寿命。

solution:
In general circumstances:

$$
\begin{aligned}
H &= \frac{1}{2 m}(\boldsymbol{p} + e \boldsymbol{A})^{2} - \boldsymbol{\mu} \cdot \boldsymbol{B} \\
\frac{\mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{\mu}}{\mathrm{~d} t} &= \frac{1}{\mathrm{i} \hbar}[\boldsymbol{\mu}, H] = \frac{1}{\mathrm{i} \hbar}\left(\frac{e \hbar}{2 m}\right)^{2}\left[\sigma_{\alpha} \boldsymbol{e}_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\beta} B_{\beta}\right] \\
&= \frac{1}{\mathrm{i} \hbar}\left(\frac{e \hbar}{2 m}\right)^{2} \boldsymbol{e}_{\alpha} B_{\beta}\left[\sigma_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\beta}\right] \\
&= \frac{1}{\mathrm{i} \hbar}\left(\frac{e \hbar}{2 m}\right)^{2} 2 \mathrm{i} \varepsilon_{\alpha \beta \gamma} \boldsymbol{e}_{\alpha} B_{\beta} \sigma_{\gamma} = \frac{e}{m} \boldsymbol{B} \times \boldsymbol{\mu}
\end{aligned}
$$

引入时间变化因子后，与时间有关的波函数为

\begin{equation*}
\Psi(r, t) = \frac{e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E^{(0)} t}}{C_{1} C_{2}^{\prime} - C_{1}^{\prime} C_{2}}\left[C_{2}^{\prime} \psi^{(0)} e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar} E^{(1)} t} - C_{2} \psi^{(0)} e^{\left.-\frac{i}{\hbar} E^{(1)}\right)_{t}}\right] \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

当 $t=0$ 时，$\Psi(t) = \psi_{1}^{(0)}$。将式（1）代入式（2），$\Psi(t)$ 变成 $\psi_{1}^{(0)}$ 与 $\psi_{2}^{(0)}$ 的线性组合， $\psi_{1}^{(0)}$ 与 $\psi_{2}^{(0)}$ 前的系数与时间有关，而 $\psi_{2}^{(0)}$ 函数前系数的模的平方即为在 $t$ 时刻跃迁到 $\psi_{2}^{(0)}$ 的概率，即

$$
P_{21} = \frac{2|V_{12}|^{2}}{(\hbar \omega^{(1)})^{2}}\left[1 - \cos(\omega^{(1)} t)\right]
$$

由上式可知，此概率随时间以频率 $\omega^{(1)}$ 作振荡。

The unperturbed wave functions and energy levels are

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \psi_{n}(\theta)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi}} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} n \theta}, \quad n= \pm 1, \pm 2, \cdots \\
& E_{n}=\frac{n^{2} \hbar^{2}}{2 m a^{2}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus, we only need to consider the two states \(n= \pm 1\), which are degenerate. The perturbation matrix is

\[
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & -\frac{\mathrm{i} A}{4} \\
\frac{\mathrm{i} A}{4} & 0
\end{pmatrix}
\]

Diagonalizing this matrix gives the two zeroth-order wave functions as

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\psi_{1}^{\prime}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(\mathrm{i}|1\rangle+|-1\rangle), & \Delta E_{1}^{(1)}=-\frac{A}{4} \\
\psi_{2}^{\prime}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(|1\rangle-\mathrm{i}|-1\rangle), & \Delta E_{2}^{(1)}=\frac{A}{4}
\end{array}
\]

Consider the following inequality

\begin{equation*}
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\left|\alpha x \psi+\frac{\mathrm{d} \psi}{\mathrm{~d} x}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} x > 0 \tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Since the integrand is an absolute value, the inequality obviously holds, where $\alpha$ is any real constant. The right side of the above equation can be written as

$$
\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\left(\alpha x \psi+\frac{\mathrm{d} \psi}{\mathrm{~d} x}\right)\left(\alpha x \psi^{*}+\frac{\mathrm{d} \psi^{*}}{\mathrm{~d} x}\right) \mathrm{d} x
$$

After expanding the above equation, it can be divided into three terms, which are respectively

\begin{align*}
& \alpha^{2} \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty} x^{2}|\psi|^{2} \mathrm{~d} x = \alpha^{2}(\delta x)^{2} \tag{2}\\
& \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}\left(\alpha x \frac{\mathrm{~d} \psi^{*}}{\mathrm{~d} x} \psi+\alpha x \psi^{*} \frac{\mathrm{~d} \psi}{\mathrm{~d} x}\right) \mathrm{d} x = \alpha \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty} x \frac{\mathrm{~d}|\psi|^{2}}{\mathrm{~d} x} \mathrm{~d} x = -\alpha \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty}|\psi|^{2} \mathrm{~d} x = -\alpha \tag{3}\\
& \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty} \frac{\mathrm{d} \psi^{*}}{\mathrm{~d} x} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{~d} \psi}{\mathrm{~d} x} \mathrm{~d} x = -\int_{-\infty}^{+\infty} \psi^{*} \frac{\mathrm{~d}^{2} \psi}{\mathrm{~d} x^{2}} \mathrm{~d} x = \frac{1}{\hbar^{2}} \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty} \psi^{*} \hat{p}_{x}^{2} \psi \mathrm{~d} x = \frac{1}{\hbar^{2}}\left(\delta p_{x}\right)^{2} \tag{4}
\end{align*}

Substituting equations (2), (3), and (4) into equation (1), we obtain

$$
\alpha^{2}(\delta x)^{2}-\alpha+\frac{1}{\hbar^{2}}\left(\delta p_{x}\right)^{2} \geqslant 0
$$

If this quadratic equation in terms of $\alpha$ is positive for all $\alpha$, its discriminant must be negative, giving the following inequality

\begin{equation*}
\delta x \delta p_{x} \geq \frac{1}{2} \hbar \tag{5}
\end{equation*}

From equation (5), it can be seen that the minimum possible value of $\delta x \delta p_{x}$ is $\frac{1}{2} \hbar$.

**Solution Method 1:** When \( x < 0 \), the wave function remains in the form as in equation (1). For \( 0 < x < t \), the Schrödinger equation is

\[
-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m} \nabla^{2} \psi = 0
\]

If \( \psi \) takes the form: \( \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{y} \cdot y} \cdot \mathrm{e}^{k x} \), then

\[
-k^{\prime 2} + k^{2} = 0, \quad k = \pm k^{\prime}
\]

Thus, the wave function for \( 0 < x < t \) is

\[
\psi_{2}(x, y) = \left(a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} x} + b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} x}\right) \mathrm{e}^{i k_{y} \cdot y}
\]

Overall, we have

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
x < 0, & \psi_{1}(x) = \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} x} + r \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} k_{x} x} \\
0 < x < t, & \psi_{2}(x) = a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} x} + b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} x} \\
x > t, & \psi_{3}(x) = c \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} x}
\end{array}
\]

Where

\[
k_{x} = \sqrt{\frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}}} \cos \theta, \quad k^{\prime} = \sqrt{\frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}}} \sin \theta
\]

Only the \( x \) component is written here. The \( y \) component is simply \( \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{y} \cdot y} \).

\[
k_{y} = \sqrt{\frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}}} \sin \theta
\]

All boundary conditions are

\[
\begin{gathered}
\left\{
\begin{array}{l}
1+r = a+b \\
\mathrm{i} k_{x}(1-r) = k^{\prime}(a-b) \\
c \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} t} = a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} t} + b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}
\end{array}
\right. \\
\mathrm{i} k_{x} \cdot c \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} t} = k^{\prime} a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} t} - k^{\prime} b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}
\end{gathered}
\]

Solving, we have

\[
\begin{gathered}
r = \frac{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} - 1}{1 - \beta^{2} \mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t}}, \quad \beta = \frac{k^{\prime} - \mathrm{i} k_{x}}{k^{\prime} + \mathrm{i} k_{x}} \\
|R|^{2} = |r|^{2} = \frac{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta}
\end{gathered}
\]

**Solution Method 2:** The problem can also be solved by using the method of amplitude superposition, similar to the case of a Fabry-Perot interferometer in optics.

Only considering the \( x \) component, let \( T_{12}, R_{12} \) represent the amplitude transmission and reflection coefficients for the wave from medium 1 to medium 2 respectively. Let \( T_{21}, R_{21} \) represent the amplitude transmission and reflection coefficients for the wave from medium 2 to medium 1 respectively. Given that the incident wave amplitude is 1, the amplitude of the wave emerging from medium 2 is

\[
\begin{aligned}
T & = T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \cdot T_{21} + T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \cdot R_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta} R_{21} \cdot T_{21} + T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \cdot \left(R_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta} R_{21}\right)^{2} \cdot T_{21} + \cdots \\
& = T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} T_{21} \left[1 + R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta} + \left(R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta}\right)^{2} + \cdots\right] = T_{12} T_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \frac{1}{1 - R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Where \( \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \) is the attenuation coefficient of the wave traveling from one interface to the other in medium 2.

\[
\delta = k^{\prime} t, \quad k^{\prime} = \sqrt{2mE(1 - \cos^{2} \theta)} / \hbar = \sqrt{2mE} \sin \theta / \hbar
\]

Using the result from (1)

\[
R_{12} = \left(k_{1 x} - k_{2 x}\right) / \left(k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}\right), \quad T_{12} = 1 + R_{12} = 2 k_{1} / \left(k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}\right)
\]

However,

\[
\begin{aligned}
& k_{1 x} = \sqrt{2mE} \cos \theta / \hbar \\
& k_{2 x} = \mathrm{i} k^{\prime} = \mathrm{i} \sqrt{2mE} \sin \theta / \hbar
\end{aligned}
\]

So,

\[
\begin{aligned}
& T_{12} = \frac{2 k_{1 x}}{k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}} = \frac{2 \cos \theta}{\cos \theta + \mathrm{i} \sin \theta} = 2 \cos \theta \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} \theta} \\
& T_{21} = \frac{2 k_{2 x}}{k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}} = \frac{2 \sin \theta}{\cos \theta + \mathrm{i} \sin \theta} = 2 \mathrm{i} \sin \theta \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} \theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
R_{21} = \frac{k_{2 x} - k_{1 x}}{k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}} = \frac{\mathrm{i} \sin \theta - \cos \theta}{\mathrm{i} \sin \theta + \cos \theta} = \mathrm{e}^{-2 \mathrm{i} \theta}
\]

Thus,

\[
\begin{aligned}
T & = T_{12} T_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \frac{1}{1 - R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta}} \\
& = \frac{4 \mathrm{i} \cos \theta \sin \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 \mathrm{i} \theta} \cdot \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}}{1 - \mathrm{e}^{-4 \mathrm{i} \theta} \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}} \\
& = \frac{2 \mathrm{i} \sin 2 \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 \mathrm{i} \theta} \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}}{1 - \mathrm{e}^{-4 \mathrm{i} \theta} \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Transmittance

\[
\begin{aligned}
|T|^{2} & = \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}}{\left(1 - \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} \cos 4 \theta\right)^{2} + \left(\mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} \sin 4 \theta\right)^{2}} \\
& = \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}}{1 + \mathrm{e}^{-4 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} \cos 4 \theta} \\
& = \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

Reflectance

\[
\begin{aligned}
1 - |T|^{2} & = 1 - \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta} \\
& = \frac{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

Where

\[
k^{\prime} = \sqrt{2mE} \sin \theta / \hbar
\]

The probability of finding the system in the \(k\) state is given by

\[
\begin{aligned}
P_{k} & =\frac{1}{\hbar^{2}}\left|H_{1k}^{\prime}\right|^{2}\left|\int_{0}^{t_{0}} \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} \omega_{kl} t} \, \mathrm{d}t \right|^{2} \\
& =\frac{1}{\hbar^{2}}\left|H_{1k}^{\prime}\right|^{2} \frac{\sin ^{2}\left(\omega_{kl} t_{0} / 2\right)}{\left(\omega_{kl} / 2\right)^{2}}, \quad t_{0}=5 \times 10^{-18} \, \text{s}
\end{aligned}
\]

Fig. 6.10(b)

\(H_{1k}^{\prime}=\int_{\frac{1}{2} a-b}^{\frac{1}{2} a+b} \frac{2}{a} \sin \left(\frac{\pi x}{a}\right) \sin \left(\frac{k \pi x}{a}\right) V_{0} \, \mathrm{d}x\), \quad \(b=\frac{1}{2} \times 10^{-12} \, \text{cm}\). Since \(b \ll a\), the integral can be evaluated using the mean value theorem for integrals

\[
\begin{aligned}
& H_{1k}^{\prime}=\frac{4 b}{a} V_{0} \sin \frac{\pi}{2} \sin \frac{k \pi}{2}=-2 \sin \frac{k \pi}{2} \, \text{eV} \\
& H_{12}^{\prime}=0, \quad H_{13}^{\prime}=2 \, \text{eV}, \quad H_{14}^{\prime}=0
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus,

\[
\begin{gathered}
P_{2}=P_{4}=0 \\
P_{3}=\frac{16}{\hbar^{2} \omega_{31}^{2}} \sin ^{2}\left(\frac{1}{2} \omega_{31} t_{0}\right)=1.45 \times 10^{-4}
\end{gathered}
\]

where

\[
\hbar \omega_{31}=336.6-37.4=299.2 \, \text{eV}
\]

