solution:
Assuming the ratio of nitrogen to oxygen in air is $4: 1$, i.e., $n_{N} = 4 n_{O}$, the density of air is given by

\begin{equation*}
\rho = \left[(4 \times 14) + (1 \times 16)\right] \frac{n_{0}}{10^{3} N_{\mathrm{A}}} \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

where $N_{\mathrm{A}}$ is Avogadro's constant $\left(N_{\mathrm{A}} = 6.02 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}\right)$. With the known condition $\rho = 1.20 \mathrm{~kg} \cdot \mathrm{m}^{-3}$, from equation (2) we can calculate

$$
n_{0} = 1.003 \times 10^{25} \mathrm{~m}^{-3}
$$

From the above expression and the given conditions, we can easily find

$$
\alpha = \sigma_{\mathrm{N} \text{total}} n_{\mathrm{N}} + \sigma_{\mathrm{O} \text{total}} n_{\mathrm{O}} = 0.057 \mathrm{~m}^{-1}
$$

